window.docContents[61].resolve({"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Generalised-continued-fractions-and-their-convergents/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Generalised-continued-fractions-and-their-convergents--Convergents-of-a-Continued-Fraction":{"contents":"The -th convergent  of a generalised continued fraction () is computed\nfrom the continuants  — the numerator (nums) and denominator (dens) — via the\nthree-term recurrence\n\n\nand the -th convergent is . mathlib stores the continuant pairs\nas the stream contsAux, with conts, nums, dens, and convs derived from it; the alternative\nconvs' evaluates the truncated fraction directly, and the two agree.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence\u0009Generalised continued fractions and their convergents","header":"9.2.2. Convergents of a Continued Fraction","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Generalised-continued-fractions-and-their-convergents/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Generalised-continued-fractions-and-their-convergents--Convergents-of-a-Continued-Fraction"},"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Modular-forms-and-cusp-forms/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Modular-forms-and-cusp-forms--Cusp-forms-as-a-submodule":{"contents":"The space of cusp forms  embeds into  as a -submodule, and\nthe type  is linearly equivalent to this submodule:\n\n\nThe submodule  is cut out inside  by the\npredicate \"the constant -expansion coefficient at every cusp vanishes\" ().\nThe forgetful map sending a cusp form to the same function viewed as a modular form is\n-linear and injective, with range exactly this submodule; the equivalence\n is the linear isomorphism of\na domain onto the range of an injective linear map.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Modular and Automorphic Forms\u0009Modular forms and cusp forms","header":"6.3.3. Cusp forms as a submodule","id":"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Modular-forms-and-cusp-forms/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Modular-forms-and-cusp-forms--Cusp-forms-as-a-submodule"},"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project--Atkin___Lehner-theory-and-strong-multiplicity-one":{"contents":"Orthogonal old/new decomposition.\nThe cusp space at level  is the internal orthogonal direct sum\n\nof the old subspace and the new subspace \n(). Consequently every cusp form  has a unique decomposition\n into old and new parts.\nFormalised in LeanModularForms: the projections HeckeRing.GL2.oldPart and newPart, built on cuspFormsNew — sorry-free.Depends on:  \n\nBoth facts are linear algebra over the Petersson inner product, which is positive-definite on\n (). Trivial intersection\n holds because a form in both a subspace and its orthogonal\ncomplement is orthogonal to itself, hence of Petersson norm zero, hence zero. The spanning property\nis the standard fact that a subspace and its orthogonal complement span any finite-dimensional space\nwith a nondegenerate inner product. Together these give the internal direct sum and the unique\nold/new decomposition.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Modular and Automorphic Forms\u0009Results from the LeanModularForms project","header":"6.8.9. Atkin–Lehner theory and strong multiplicity one","id":"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project--Atkin___Lehner-theory-and-strong-multiplicity-one"},"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/The-upper-half-plane-and-the-M___bius-action/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--The-upper-half-plane-and-the-M___bius-action--The-upper-half-plane":{"contents":"The upper half-plane  is the set of complex numbers with strictly positive imaginary\npart:\n\nIt is realised in mathlib as the subtype of  carrying the positivity condition\n.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Modular and Automorphic Forms\u0009The upper half-plane and the Möbius action","header":"6.1.1. The upper half-plane","id":"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/The-upper-half-plane-and-the-M___bius-action/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--The-upper-half-plane-and-the-M___bius-action--The-upper-half-plane"}});